es of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":7,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Wentworth II was born in 1283, in North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Wentworth, was 19 and his mother, Dionysia Rotherfield, was 14. He married Isabella Pollington in 1301, in Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1308, in Wentworth, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1283–1308":"1283–1308","1290–1325":"1290–1325","1285–1360":"1285–1360","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1308–1413":"1308–1413","1265–1308":"1265–1308","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1413":"1413","1325":"1325","about 1308":"umbes 1308","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1288":"1288","1265":"1265","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, Inglaterra":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England","North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England":"North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1283–1308":"1283–1308","1290–1325":"1290–1325","1285–1360":"1285–1360","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1308–1413":"1308–1413",